I'm kind of sporadic with the archives, but I do find them much more challenging than most of the recent puzzles.

@CCNY, you were interested in solving patterns.

I always start with the acrosses and do them in numerical order, filling in anything that comes to mind immediately.  I try not to linger on a clue for more than a second or two.  I then do the downs in numerical order.  I may zip through the downs as well, but towards the end of the week I tend to pause in an area if I have some sort of foothold, and focus on that area.  After I've been through all the downs I look for more low-hanging fruit, answers that have more than one letter filled in due to the crosses.

I use the timer, and am happy whenever I get a new personal best, but I do not rush as it ruins my enjoyment.  I am not interested in being a speed solver.  I stopped using lookups shortly after starting to solve online; my interest is in solving a puzzle on my own, even if it takes a long time.  There has been more than one Saturday (and Sunday) puzzle where it took me over two hours to get the gold.  But my online solving started about the same time I retired, so I have the luxury of spending more time on the puzzle than the working folks care to.

@G

